  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which is the best book for maths?",
  "response": "The \"best\" book for math can vary depending on your specific needs, skill level, and the areas of mathematics you're interested in. However, here are a few highly recommended books that are widely appreciated for their comprehensive coverage and clear explanations:\n\n1. **For General Mathematics and Problem Solving:**\n   - **\"A Mathematician's Lament\" by Paul Lockhart** - This book provides a philosophical perspective on mathematics and is great for sparking an interest in the subject.\n   - **\"The Art of Problem Solving\" series** - Excellent for high school students and those preparing for math competitions.\n\n2. **For Calculus:**\n   - **\"Calculus\" by Michael Spivak** - Known for its rigorous approach and clear explanations, this is a favorite among students and professionals.\n   - **\"Calculus: Early Transcendentals\" by James Stewart** - A widely used textbook in university courses, offering a comprehensive introduction to calculus.\n\n3. **For Linear Algebra:**\n   - **\"Linear Algebra Done Right\" by Sheldon Axler** - Highly praised for its clear and thorough presentation of linear algebra concepts.\n\n4. **For Abstract Algebra:**\n   - **\"Abstract Algebra\" by David S. Dummit and Richard M. Foote** - A comprehensive and well-structured textbook on abstract algebra.\n\n5. **For Number Theory:**\n   - **\"A Course in Number Theory\" by Henryk Iwaniec and Emmanuel Kowalski** - A detailed and advanced treatment of number theory.\n\n6. **For Recreational Mathematics:**\n   - **\"The Man Who Loved Only Numbers\" by Paul Hoffman** - A biography of Paul Erd\u0151s that also delves into various interesting mathematical problems.\n\nIf you have a specific area of interest or a particular level you're studying at, feel free to provide more details, and I can give you a more tailored recommendation!",
